Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the US government represents a massive bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had been steadily increasing in the face of falling home prices.
Now that the government is fully backing Fannie and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to bear all the costs that are not covered by the insufficient financial resources of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the most overtly capitalist country in the world?
Do the esteemed principles of capitalism not include that those who believed in the real estate bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers have to suffer for the mistakes of others now?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly outlined.
But they are not.
Most importantly, it is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost US taxpayers in the end. It might prevent further systemic effects that would force the financial sector and thus the world economy to its knees.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
Zudem wurden die von Fannie und Freddie ausgegebenen Anleihen weithin so angesehen, als wären sie mit einer stillschweigenden Garantie der US-Regierung ausgestattet.
Obwohl es keine offizielle Garantie gab, könnte das Ausbleiben einer Rettungsaktion seitens der US-Regierung das Vertrauen in Staatspapiere und – weil sie mit diesen in Verbindung gebracht werden – auch in andere Finanztitel untergraben.
The problems extend far beyond the US economy.
The global economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative booms and crashes in asset values, which bring questions of trust, as well as fairness, into the equation.
Similarly, in many other countries, current housing market booms are coming to an end, and they may be facing the same hardships – and the same moral dilemmas – that the US economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem are not only the housing markets.
The stock markets are also involved.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose by a factor of 5 between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose by a factor of 5 in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar booms and crashes in stock markets have occurred in many other countries.
As long as they continued, the preceding boom phases of these economic downturns led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a loss of confidence could seize the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary – not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no exact science of confidence, no way to predict how people will react when, in the face of collapsing markets, aid fails to arrive.
People's reactions to these events depend on their emotions and their sense of justice.
The described booms and crashes have caused a significant redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested in the stock market or real estate market did well or poorly depending on timing.
People will judge the fairness of these results based on what was told to them and the unspoken promises they derived from it.
What was told to people in all these countries about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
There is unfortunately no way to find out.
Policymakers can only react generally and cannot treat each case individually.
We know that the recent economic growth in many countries was spectacular.
But were the capital investments sold too expensively into their markets?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere led people to believe that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
Surely, it is certain that although there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – the majority of the losers in this game are not starving.
Yet we cannot unhesitatingly conclude from this that all their losses should be left untouched.
The nagging problem is one of "faith and trust."
National economies thrive only when "faith and trust" prevail.
The current situation, in which speculative upsurges have driven the world economy – and now, after their collapse, are driving it into recession – suggests that people who have extolled certain capital investments have done so against faith and trust.
Take the investors who held Fannie and Freddie bonds.
Although the U.S. government never officially promised to bail them out, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
This agency, however, never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The top of the government never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is in the process of transforming and discovering the capitalism and its power, national economies.
Yet capitalism relies on trust and faith.
A treatment perceived as unfair can be deadly for economic growth, because it means that people lose their trust in companies and therefore are less willing to make their valuable capital and their labor force available to them.
Is such an outcome morally preferable to a bailout?
